    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Fairness in the Bronx</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter by William Goodman of Center for Constitutional Rights sees implicitly racist assumptions in decision to move Diallo shooting case from the Bronx to Albany (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In ''Mixed Verdicts in Police Cases in Albany'' (column, Dec. 29), Matthew Purdy assumes a wounded tone on behalf of Albany jurors and proposes that white jurors can be fair. Mr. Purdy ignores the grossly insulting, and implicitly racist, assumption in the decision to move the Diallo case to Albany from the Bronx: that Bronx jurors could not be fair.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In ''Mixed Verdicts in Police Cases in Albany'' (column, Dec. 29), Matthew Purdy assumes a wounded tone on behalf of Albany jurors and proposes that white jurors can be fair. Mr. Purdy ignores the grossly insulting, and implicitly racist, assumption in the decision to move the Diallo case to Albany from the Bronx: that Bronx jurors could not be fair.</p>
        <p>Although Mr. Purdy cites a few damage verdicts on behalf of victims of police brutality, he is unable to identify a single criminal prosecution of a police officer in which an Albany jury convicted.</p>
        <p>The sad tendency of American courts is to prevent African-Americans from sitting in criminal judgment of white police officers charged with crimes against persons of color.</p>
        <p>WILLIAM GOODMAN  Legal Director, Center  for Constitutional Rights  New York, Dec. 29, 1999</p>
      </block>
